First Amended Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

evidence.text: 1. Declaring that the termination of SEVIS status for Plaintiffs and all similarly situated F-1 visa holders—who have not been convicted of any criminal offense, have maintained academic standing, and are otherwise in compliance with the terms of their visa—was unlawful, and that their SEVIS records, F-1 status, and visas shall be restored immediately;
evidence.source_document: First Amended Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: Plaintiff: Declaring that the termination of SEVIS status for Plaintiffs and all similarly situated F-1 visa holders—who have not been convicted of any criminal offense, have maintained academic standing, and are otherwise in compliance with the terms of their visa—was unlawful, and that their SEVIS records, F-1 status, and visas shall be restored immediately;

evidence.text: 2. Preliminarily and permanently enjoining Defendants Noem and Lyons from further SEVIS terminations without lawful process;
evidence.source_document: First Amended Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: Plaintiff: Preliminarily and permanently enjoining Defendants Noem and Lyons from further SEVIS terminations without lawful process;

evidence.text: 3. Issuing a preliminary and permanent injunction requiring Defendant Rubio to withdraw the effective-in-the-future revocation of the F-1 visas for Plaintiffs Tao, Wu, and Li, and all similarly situated F-1 visa holders—whose visa revocations were part of mass SEVIS terminations in April 2025 and who have not been convicted of any criminal offense, have maintained academic standing, and are otherwise in compliance with the terms of their visa— and prohibiting Defendant Rubio from further revocations of those visas beyond the statutory authority of 8 U.S.C. § 1201(i).
evidence.source_document: First Amended Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: Plaintiff: Issuing a preliminary and permanent injunction requiring Defendant Rubio to withdraw the effective-in-the-future revocation of the F-1 visas for Plaintiffs Tao, Wu, and Li, and all similarly situated F-1 visa holders—whose visa revocations were part of mass SEVIS terminations in April 2025 and who have not been convicted of any criminal offense, have maintained academic standing, and are otherwise in compliance with the terms of their visa— and prohibiting Defendant Rubio from further revocations of those visas beyond the statutory authority of 8 U.S.C. § 1201(i).

evidence.text: 4. Awarding costs and attorneys’ fees pursuant to the Equal Access to Justice Act, 28 U.S.C. § 2412(b);
evidence.source_document: First Amended Complaint for Declaratory and Injunctive Relief

add_extracted.value: Plaintiff: Awarding costs and attorneys’ fees pursuant to the Equal Access to Justice Act, 28 U.S.C. § 2412(b);
